Title:
New security capabilities in Event Tracing for Windows

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- Microsoft describes updates to Windows security-relevant ETW-backed event schemas to improve attribution of “who initiated” certain actions.  
- The problem addressed is misleading provenance where the process that *logs* an event (e.g., SYSTEM/LSASS as an “acting deputy”) differs from the process that *caused* the action, creating gaps for DFIR and detection engineering.  
- Updated events now include additional payload fields (not just header) such as initiating/client Process ID and Process Start Key (a boot-unique sequence number) to correlate actions to the true originating process.  
- The post highlights specific Security-Auditing and Eventlog provider events (service install, scheduled task operations, audit policy changes, and log clearing) that now carry these fields.  
- It shows how to interpret the new data by correlating a scheduled task creation event (4698) with process creation (4688) to validate parent/child relationships and provenance.  
- Useful for Blue Teams (DFIR, detection engineering, SIEM/EDR telemetry consumers) and also for Red Teams to understand improved visibility around persistence and log-tampering actions.

Technical Focus:
- Event Tracing for Windows (ETW) event schema/versioning
- Event provenance / “acting deputy” vs causal process attribution
- Process Start Key and Process ID correlation across boots
- Windows Security Auditing event IDs (4688, 4697–4702, 4719)
- Event log clearing telemetry (1102, 104) via Microsoft-Windows-Eventlog provider
- ETW control/collection APIs (StartTraceA, EnableTraceEx2)

Use Cases:
- Build higher-fidelity detections for scheduled task persistence and service installation by attributing initiating process
- Investigate audit policy changes (4719) with reliable initiating process context
- Detect and triage log clearing attempts (1102/104) with process provenance
- Improve timeline correlation in DFIR by linking security events to process creation telemetry (4688)
- Validate SIEM parsing/mapping to ensure payload fields are ingested (not only header fields)

Keywords:
ETW, Event Tracing for Windows, Windows Security Auditing, Microsoft-Windows-Eventlog, event schema, event versioning, process provenance, acting deputy, ClientProcessID, ParentProcessID, Process Start Key, ExecutionProcessID, Event Viewer, StartTraceA, EnableTraceEx2, event 4688, event 4698, event 4719, event 1102, scheduled tasks, SchTasks.exe, lsass.exe, audit policy change, log clearing, DFIR, detection engineering, MITRE ATT&CK T1053.005